sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K1969006
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: S. cerevisiae GPA2 with 5 amino acids from human G(s) alpha-subunit
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is DNA sequence coding for S. cerevisiae guanine nucleotide-binding protein subunit alpha (GPA2) with 5 amino acids at C terminus replaced by corresponding part of human G(s) alpha-subunit (alpha-S1). The strategy of making yeast???human chimeric G-protein, in which the carboxyl-terminal 5 amino acid residues of yeast G alpha subunit are replaced by the equivalent residues from human Gs proteins, has been shown to improve signal transmission in GPCR engineered yeast according to recent literature.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Yijie Lai
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: It's a combination of yeast Gpa2 coding sequence (from genomic DNA of S. cerevisiae), and human G(s) alpha-subunit (from genomic DNA of human).
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: The endogenous G proteins may not be able to couple with the mammalian GPCRs efficiently, so we do the modifications at C terminal residues to yield better results.
